                    "description": "2015-2016 Scientific coordinator of USAID funded core project to evaluate effects of TB control interventions on TB transmission in multiple countries. \n\nPast TB related research experience:\n\u25aa\tTB incidence among cohorts of children and adolescents in South Africa, Uganda and Kenya, to prepare for vaccine trials, including survey design\n\u25aa\tNationwide TB Epidemiological assessment\n\u25aa\tTransmission of TB using molecular epidemiology\n\u25aa\tMonitoring and evaluation of programs \n\u25aa\tMonitoring of screening for TB in high risk groups (migrants, health care workers, travelers, smokers) \n\u25aa\tDiagnostics of latent tuberculosis infection and TB in low and high incidence countries\n\u25aa\tAssessment of treatment outcomes in Europe using routine surveillance data \n\u2022\tContact tracing\n\u25aa\tImproving TB treatment outcomes\n\u25aa\tSurveys of annual risk of TB infection\n\u25aa\tAssess accuracy of surveillance systems\n\nMore functions:\n\u25aa\t2011-2014, head of the Knowledge, Research and Policy unit. Managed a unit of 12 mainly senior TB consultants in all sub-specialties of TB control. We determined KNCV strategy, linked global strategies to organisational strategies and country strategies; kept oversight in KNCVs research portfolio and managed knowledge and organisational learning. This unit was abolished in 2015.\n\u25aa\tAssisting countries in performing TB operational research by facilitating on the job and classroom operational research training. \n\u25aa\tTeaching on tuberculosis epidemiology and tuberculosis screening to MSc students from Netherlands Institute of Health sciences (NIHES), Institute of Social Studies (ISS) and ErasmusMC, Netherlands.\n\u25aa\tWriting grant proposals: Grants obtained from Zon-Mw, EDCTP, ECDC, Sequela, Aeras, USAID.\n\u25aa\tSupervising PhD students: all 5 successfully obtained their PhD\n\nInternational experience: South Africa, Uganda, Kenya, Egypt, Mozambique, Zambia, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Tanzania",
